
00:00:01,468 --> 00:00:03,437
NARRATOR:
Tonight on "Shark Tank"...

00:00:03,437 --> 00:00:06,006
Things get even more heated
when the men take on the women.

00:00:06,006 --> 00:00:08,141
The difference between us
and the girls

00:00:08,141 --> 00:00:10,944
is that I actually own
businesses that I can
place orders for.

00:00:10,944 --> 00:00:12,079
Are you sick?

00:00:12,079 --> 00:00:14,615
Why is it every time
there's a female product

00:00:14,615 --> 00:00:16,950
on this show,
you guys go out right away?

00:00:16,950 --> 00:00:18,485
No, it's -- that's crap.

00:00:18,485 --> 00:00:20,821
NARRATOR: In the tank,
hopeful entrepreneurs

00:00:20,821 --> 00:00:23,557
get a once-in-a-lifetime chance
to pitch the sharks

00:00:23,557 --> 00:00:25,225
in hopes
of getting an investment

00:00:25,225 --> 00:00:27,427
to start, grow,
or save their businesses.

00:00:27,427 --> 00:00:29,129
[ laughter ]
No!

00:00:29,129 --> 00:00:31,098
The entrepreneurs
must convince a shark

00:00:31,098 --> 00:00:32,900
to invest the full amount
they're asking for,

00:00:32,900 --> 00:00:35,269
or they'll walk away
with nothing.

00:00:35,269 --> 00:00:37,037
This is fraudulent behavior.

00:00:37,037 --> 00:00:38,505
Listen, you're just taking
the guy down

00:00:38,505 --> 00:00:39,873
and making him feel
like he can't do this.

00:00:39,873 --> 00:00:41,108
I'm not finished
taking him down!

00:00:41,108 --> 00:00:43,677
NARRATOR: If the sharks hear
a great idea...

00:00:43,677 --> 00:00:44,645
What was your profit?

00:00:44,645 --> 00:00:46,780
$2.65 million.
You're killing it!

00:00:46,780 --> 00:00:49,850
NARRATOR: ...They're ready
to invest using their own money.

00:00:49,850 --> 00:00:51,251
And they're willing
to fight each other

00:00:51,251 --> 00:00:52,686
for a piece of the action.

00:00:52,686 --> 00:00:54,154
I'll take that deal.
Wait. We didn't hear it.

00:00:54,154 --> 00:00:55,689
I'm a big guy.
Whoa, whoa!

00:00:55,689 --> 00:00:58,492
Do we have a deal?
Wait. You know the histories
of Barb and I.

00:00:58,492 --> 00:01:01,194
It's never gonna go
into retail.
How insulting!

00:01:01,194 --> 00:01:03,230
Barb, want to go in with me?
O'LEARY:
If 30% is available --

00:01:03,230 --> 00:01:05,065
no problem at all, baby.
I'm right there with you.
okay.

00:01:05,065 --> 00:01:06,300
It is a guy thing.
I love it.

00:01:06,300 --> 00:01:08,602
You need to say yes
now to us.

00:01:08,602 --> 00:01:09,770
What the hell is this?!

00:01:09,770 --> 00:01:10,771
You're just
in a lousy mood today.

00:01:10,771 --> 00:01:12,539
Don't turn your back
in the tank.

00:01:14,575 --> 00:01:15,943
NARRATOR:
Who are the sharks?

00:01:17,010 --> 00:01:20,480
They're self-made millionaire
and billionaire investors

00:01:20,480 --> 00:01:23,016
who are entrepreneurs
themselves.

00:01:23,016 --> 00:01:25,719
Kevin O'Leary
is a venture capitalist

00:01:25,719 --> 00:01:28,121
who turned a $10,000 loan

00:01:28,121 --> 00:01:32,726
into a software business
worth $4.2 billion.

00:01:33,827 --> 00:01:37,230
Barbara Corcoran went
from waiting tables in Manhattan

00:01:37,230 --> 00:01:39,900
to building the city's
preeminent real-estate empire.

00:01:41,234 --> 00:01:44,438
Robert Herjavec, the son
of an immigrant factory worker,

00:01:44,438 --> 00:01:46,306
is now a technology mogul

00:01:46,306 --> 00:01:50,844
who sold his first internet
companies for over $350 million.

00:01:51,945 --> 00:01:54,348
Lori Greiner, the queen of QVC,

00:01:54,348 --> 00:01:58,418
holds over 100 patents and
has launched over 300 products,

00:01:58,418 --> 00:02:02,222
grossing over a half a billion
dollars in retail sales.

00:02:02,222 --> 00:02:04,257
And Mark Cuban,

00:02:04,257 --> 00:02:06,193
notorious billionaire
entrepreneur, tech guru,

00:02:06,193 --> 00:02:20,440
and the outspoken owner
of the NBA's Dallas Mavericks.

00:02:20,440 --> 00:02:23,377
First into the tank
is a dynamic product

00:02:23,377 --> 00:02:26,046
designed to help businesses
attract customers.

00:02:31,518 --> 00:02:33,854
Hi, sharks.
I'm Scott Adams.

00:02:33,854 --> 00:02:35,589
Hi, sharks.
I'm Josh Faherty.

00:02:35,589 --> 00:02:37,758
And we're from Sacramento,
California.

00:02:37,758 --> 00:02:40,327
We are the inventors
of Velocity Signs.

00:02:40,327 --> 00:02:42,796
We are seeking $225,000

00:02:42,796 --> 00:02:46,099
in exchange for 15% equity stake
in our business.

00:02:46,099 --> 00:02:48,869
One day, I was working
in Los Angeles,

00:02:48,869 --> 00:02:51,605
driving to a client meeting,
and it was 110 degrees outside.

00:02:51,605 --> 00:02:55,375
I looked over on the corner
and saw a poor guy

00:02:55,375 --> 00:02:58,378
waving a sign around,
dripping sweat.

00:02:58,378 --> 00:02:59,279
His shirt was wet.

00:02:59,279 --> 00:03:00,414
Then he rested
in a shaded area

00:03:00,414 --> 00:03:03,283
with his sign facedown.

00:03:03,283 --> 00:03:04,818
My first thought was,
"poor guy!

00:03:04,818 --> 00:03:06,386
He's gonna die
of heat exhaustion."

00:03:06,386 --> 00:03:09,489
My second thought -- "There's
got to be a better way."

00:03:09,489 --> 00:03:11,758
That's when we launched
Velocity Signs.

00:03:11,758 --> 00:03:14,127
[ laughter ]

00:03:14,127 --> 00:03:16,596
Portable, rechargeable,
interchangeable,

00:03:16,596 --> 00:03:18,865
self-standing,
and most importantly,

00:03:18,865 --> 00:03:21,034
they're made to grab
your attention

00:03:21,034 --> 00:03:22,536
with its unique movement.

00:03:22,536 --> 00:03:24,237
Sharks,
invest in Velocity Signs.

00:03:24,237 --> 00:03:27,107
Help us shake our way into every
business all over the world

00:03:27,107 --> 00:03:29,609
and put some velocity
back in the American economy.

00:03:29,609 --> 00:03:32,746
Do you guys got, like,
a B.B. gun or something?

00:03:32,746 --> 00:03:34,448
It's like we're at the arcade.
Bam, bam.

00:03:34,448 --> 00:03:37,217
[ laughter ]
Down goes Kevin.

00:03:37,217 --> 00:03:39,453
You're the guy that
looks like something
out of a horror movie.

00:03:39,453 --> 00:03:41,154
[ laughing ] Hey!

00:03:41,154 --> 00:03:43,256
How substantial are they? Are
they on their feet s-securely?

00:03:43,256 --> 00:03:44,558
ADAMS: Good question.

00:03:44,558 --> 00:03:47,627
They're 165 pounds, so it's
really hard to tip them over.

00:03:47,627 --> 00:03:48,729
So, how much
does this cost?

00:03:48,729 --> 00:03:51,565
From $18.99 all the way
up to $2,850.

00:03:51,565 --> 00:03:52,599
And how many
have you sold?

00:03:52,599 --> 00:03:54,935
We've sold 125
over the last 12 months.

00:03:56,136 --> 00:03:57,404
That's all, huh?

00:03:57,404 --> 00:03:59,239
125 a year.

00:03:59,239 --> 00:04:02,209
So, about $257,000
for over 12 months.

00:04:02,209 --> 00:04:03,944
And what -- what's your cost
on a typical --

00:04:03,944 --> 00:04:05,145
the Cuban's gonna cost you

00:04:05,145 --> 00:04:07,347
about -- about $1,000
cost of goods sold.

00:04:07,347 --> 00:04:08,482
To you.

00:04:08,482 --> 00:04:10,283
To -- to make it, for me.
Correct.
Oh, okay.

00:04:10,283 --> 00:04:12,252
How effective
h-have you found

00:04:12,252 --> 00:04:14,154
these are
for your customers?

00:04:14,154 --> 00:04:15,756
What do they tell you back?

00:04:15,756 --> 00:04:19,626
On average, our clients get
a 15% return on investment.

00:04:19,626 --> 00:04:20,794
CUBAN:
What kind of clients?

00:04:20,794 --> 00:04:22,996
Our biggest client right now
is little Caesars,

00:04:22,996 --> 00:04:26,333
who's got 3,560 locations
worldwide

00:04:26,333 --> 00:04:27,667
in 50 different countries.

00:04:27,667 --> 00:04:30,871
How many days do I have
to pay a student

00:04:30,871 --> 00:04:33,774
to spin signs before I pay
for one of these?

00:04:33,774 --> 00:04:37,611
I think the best analogy is
that our machines run nonstop,

00:04:37,611 --> 00:04:40,180
so you're getting full use
out of these machines

00:04:40,180 --> 00:04:42,916
versus human sign-spinners,
who have to take breaks.

00:04:42,916 --> 00:04:44,785
They, uh --
they're hard to manage.

00:04:44,785 --> 00:04:46,787
They get tired.
They walk off on the job.
I hate those humans.

00:04:46,787 --> 00:04:48,822
The turnover's
extremely high.
GREINER: You know what?
I'll tell you something else.

00:04:48,822 --> 00:04:50,257
I always feel sorry
for them.
CORCORAN: Yes.

00:04:50,257 --> 00:04:51,558
They have a job, Lori!

00:04:51,558 --> 00:04:52,759
ADAMS:
We're creating jobs.

00:04:52,759 --> 00:04:54,728
If you -- you can have
that employee

00:04:54,728 --> 00:04:56,296
that you run out
waving the sign

00:04:56,296 --> 00:04:58,365
move in and do some
more productive work
for your business,

00:04:58,365 --> 00:05:00,033
because you're gonna save money

00:05:00,033 --> 00:05:02,502
by hiring
that st-- human sign-spinner,

00:05:02,502 --> 00:05:05,205
but you're also gonna increase
sales by an average of 15%.

00:05:05,205 --> 00:05:06,706
That's $90,000 in new revenue

00:05:06,706 --> 00:05:08,542
you can put
to hiring new people.

00:05:08,542 --> 00:05:09,843
Well, that's
a decent answer.

00:05:09,843 --> 00:05:11,211
So they'll be displaced.
Okay.

00:05:11,211 --> 00:05:12,712
They'll be -- they'll be hired
in other positions

00:05:12,712 --> 00:05:13,980
that businesses
are gonna be hiring for.

00:05:13,980 --> 00:05:16,116
You're a good salesman,
Scott.
Thank you.

00:05:16,116 --> 00:05:18,185
What do you want to do
with the money?

00:05:18,185 --> 00:05:20,020
What's the world-domination
plan?

00:05:20,020 --> 00:05:24,057
We are gonna sell 1,200 units
over the next 12 months.

00:05:24,057 --> 00:05:25,725
We're gonna hire
eight sales reps,

00:05:25,725 --> 00:05:27,861
and we're gonna hire
four administrative staff.

00:05:27,861 --> 00:05:30,263
The other challenge
has been --

00:05:30,263 --> 00:05:33,133
I think it's clever, but I
invested in a billboard company

00:05:33,133 --> 00:05:34,668
many, many,
many years ago,

00:05:34,668 --> 00:05:36,937
and we deal with the --
the electronic signage,

00:05:36,937 --> 00:05:38,972
and it was a horrible,
miserable failure.

00:05:38,972 --> 00:05:40,173
I'm sorry to hear that.

00:05:40,173 --> 00:05:42,909
Now, one thing we found is
that the consumer

00:05:42,909 --> 00:05:46,813
gets very old very quickly
with the movement,

00:05:46,813 --> 00:05:48,281
and then it needs
to be changed.

00:05:48,281 --> 00:05:49,950
Right.

00:05:49,950 --> 00:05:52,586
Not a big fan of this business,
so I'm out.

00:05:52,586 --> 00:05:53,820
Okay. Robert.

00:05:54,754 --> 00:05:55,722
[ laughs ]
GREINER: Cut him off?

00:05:55,722 --> 00:05:57,357
No! No!
Gonna turn it off.

00:05:57,357 --> 00:05:59,159
[ laughter ]

00:05:59,159 --> 00:06:00,961
Smart.
O'LEARY: I love it.

00:06:00,961 --> 00:06:03,396
You never told us how much,
on your own forecast,

00:06:03,396 --> 00:06:04,965
you think you're going to make
next year.

00:06:04,965 --> 00:06:07,901
In very conservative
numbers,

00:06:07,901 --> 00:06:10,270
we're gonna
bring in $2.5 million

00:06:10,270 --> 00:06:12,505
and bring in $500,000
in sales.

00:06:12,505 --> 00:06:15,675
I would like to see a year
or two worth of sales

00:06:15,675 --> 00:06:17,444
so that we can see
what the real number is.

00:06:17,444 --> 00:06:20,814
My expectation is it'll be
a lot less than you think.

00:06:20,814 --> 00:06:23,617
I'm saying I don't know,
so I'm out.

00:06:23,617 --> 00:06:25,118
Thank you. Cut it.

00:06:25,118 --> 00:06:26,720
[ laughter ]

00:06:26,720 --> 00:06:28,121
Thank God!

00:06:28,121 --> 00:06:29,623
CUBAN:
I like the business.

00:06:29,623 --> 00:06:34,127
The problem is that once you
get one, you don't need two.

00:06:34,127 --> 00:06:35,896
I'm out.

00:06:35,896 --> 00:06:37,130
Scott, he's out.
Turn him off.

00:06:37,130 --> 00:06:38,231
I'm out. Turn me off.

00:06:38,231 --> 00:06:39,966
ADAMS: Barbara? Lori?

00:06:39,966 --> 00:06:41,768
I was thinking about
the franchises I owned

00:06:41,768 --> 00:06:42,769
of real-estate brokers.

00:06:42,769 --> 00:06:44,271
What a natural audience
for this.

00:06:44,271 --> 00:06:46,339
Absolutely.
They pull it out of the back
of their car,

00:06:46,339 --> 00:06:48,174
and they put it
for an open-house sign...

00:06:48,174 --> 00:06:51,211
Oh, wow. Absolutely.
...That nobody even wants
to ever go to anymore,

00:06:51,211 --> 00:06:52,879
'cause they're tired of seeing
the signs.

00:06:52,879 --> 00:06:55,181
And, by the way, why does she
look so much prettier than me?

00:06:55,181 --> 00:06:56,650
I'm really pissed over that.
[ laughter ]

00:06:56,650 --> 00:06:58,385
and -- and -- but here's
the problem

00:06:58,385 --> 00:07:00,587
with even
the real-estate franchisees

00:07:00,587 --> 00:07:02,689
or the individual brokers
or agents.

00:07:02,689 --> 00:07:06,626
165 pounds out of the trunk
of their car to move it.

00:07:06,626 --> 00:07:09,229
So even that perfect
application is filled with --

00:07:09,229 --> 00:07:10,230
we didn't tell you
about a new product

00:07:10,230 --> 00:07:11,364
we've been working on,
as well.

00:07:11,364 --> 00:07:13,700
It stakes in the ground
for real-estate agents.

00:07:13,700 --> 00:07:15,535
And then it wiggles.
Smaller battery used
for a short --

00:07:15,535 --> 00:07:16,770
because open houses
are all day long.

00:07:16,770 --> 00:07:18,204
Why didn't you say it?
Why didn't you tell us about it?

00:07:18,204 --> 00:07:19,639
That's a better product.

00:07:19,639 --> 00:07:20,640
But you don't have it yet,

00:07:20,640 --> 00:07:21,908
so I wish I could see
that product.

00:07:21,908 --> 00:07:23,543
Mm-hmm.
If that were the case,
I'd be in.

00:07:23,543 --> 00:07:24,678
But I'm sorry.
I'm out.

00:07:26,112 --> 00:07:29,616
But would you --
don't turn me off.

00:07:29,616 --> 00:07:30,717
Get rid of Lori.

00:07:30,717 --> 00:07:31,751
I'm really annoyed

00:07:31,751 --> 00:07:33,386
that she's looking
so good up there.

00:07:33,386 --> 00:07:35,322
Turn her off!
You don't -- you don't have
to turn Barbara off.

00:07:35,322 --> 00:07:37,557
FAHERTY: Sorry, Barbara.
Just throw a bucket of water
on her. She'll melt.

00:07:37,557 --> 00:07:39,359
GREINER: Don't turn Lori off!
She's the only one left!

00:07:39,359 --> 00:07:40,760
ADAMS: Lori.
[ laughter ]

00:07:40,760 --> 00:07:42,562
first of all, I like --

00:07:42,562 --> 00:07:44,164
you sell a ton of these
on QVC?

00:07:44,164 --> 00:07:45,799
[ laughs ]
No.

00:07:45,799 --> 00:07:48,134
CORCORAN: No way, Jose.
But I sell a lot
of other places than QVC.

00:07:48,134 --> 00:07:51,871
I think that this is
an extremely smart new way

00:07:51,871 --> 00:07:55,442
to draw attention to
brick-and-mortar retail stores

00:07:55,442 --> 00:07:57,877
that are on the street
that are hurting right now,

00:07:57,877 --> 00:07:59,779
and I think retailers
are going to really love this.

00:07:59,779 --> 00:08:02,248
I also like that you'll be
helping these smaller businesses

00:08:02,248 --> 00:08:05,385
keep their jobs
and keep their stores.

00:08:05,385 --> 00:08:11,124
So I'll offer you $225,000
for 30% of your business.

00:08:11,124 --> 00:08:14,761
And, hopefully, together,

00:08:14,761 --> 00:08:17,097
we can get this really big and
really out there everywhere,

00:08:17,097 --> 00:08:19,199
'cause every franchise
needs this.

00:08:19,199 --> 00:08:20,834
I -- we definitely see a value

00:08:20,834 --> 00:08:22,869
in your support
and your experience.

00:08:22,869 --> 00:08:24,104
O'LEARY:
I'll tell you what.

00:08:24,104 --> 00:08:25,205
If you take that deal,

00:08:25,205 --> 00:08:26,840
and Lori will have me,
I'll come in on it.

00:08:26,840 --> 00:08:29,242
I like it at that valuation.
I'll come in if you want.

00:08:29,242 --> 00:08:31,578
I'll come in as a third.
What just happened?!

00:08:31,578 --> 00:08:34,547
What just happened?

00:08:42,355 --> 00:08:44,624
NARRATOR:
Four sharks were out,

00:08:44,624 --> 00:08:45,725
but after Lori
expresses interest,

00:08:45,725 --> 00:08:47,927
Kevin and Mark
want a piece of the action.

00:08:47,927 --> 00:08:49,195
What just happened?!
What just happened?

00:08:49,195 --> 00:08:51,264
ADAMS: So, would that be
10% for Mark,

00:08:51,264 --> 00:08:53,400
10% for you,
and 10% for Lori?

00:08:53,400 --> 00:08:55,969
Yeah. We'd do that deal,
if Lori says yes.
CUBAN: Yeah.

00:08:55,969 --> 00:08:57,637
Are you okay
with that, Lori?

00:08:57,637 --> 00:09:00,006
Okay.
So, I made the offer.

00:09:00,006 --> 00:09:01,574
O'LEARY: I could sell
a lot of these.

00:09:01,574 --> 00:09:03,777
I said $225,000
at 30%, and --

00:09:03,777 --> 00:09:05,578
or better yet,
Robert, Kevin, and I

00:09:05,578 --> 00:09:07,747
could go in together
if she doesn't like it.

00:09:07,747 --> 00:09:10,750
I'm good with that.
And --

00:09:10,750 --> 00:09:12,085
oh, yeah?
then I'll go in with Lori.

00:09:12,085 --> 00:09:13,586
Wait!
Who believed in you?
No problem.

00:09:13,586 --> 00:09:14,854
ADAMS: That's
a good point, Lori.

00:09:14,854 --> 00:09:16,656
And who were all the lovely,
little sharks that said,

00:09:16,656 --> 00:09:19,559
"I don't believe in you,"
and they dropped out?

00:09:19,559 --> 00:09:21,027
O'LEARY: You know what?
I changed my mind.

00:09:21,027 --> 00:09:22,295
Instead,
because they're that way --
nobody said that!

00:09:22,295 --> 00:09:24,197
I -- Barb, want to go in
with me?

00:09:24,197 --> 00:09:27,167
If 30% is available --
no problem at all, baby.
I'm right there with you.

00:09:27,167 --> 00:09:28,701
Okay, guys, Barbara and I,

00:09:28,701 --> 00:09:33,873
we're going in together,
$225,000 at 25%?

00:09:33,873 --> 00:09:36,609
O'LEARY: Here's our deal.

00:09:36,609 --> 00:09:38,745
You get three sharks for 30% --
10% each.

00:09:38,745 --> 00:09:41,247
We have so many businesses
we can apply this to,

00:09:41,247 --> 00:09:43,716
so many contacts
we can phone for you.

00:09:43,716 --> 00:09:45,485
Oh, please.
We will set you on fire.

00:09:45,485 --> 00:09:47,020
You guys know
whose history --

00:09:47,020 --> 00:09:49,589
you know the histories
of Barb and I.

00:09:49,589 --> 00:09:51,291
This is not a QVC product!
You know what we've done.

00:09:51,291 --> 00:09:53,993
Three is always better than two.
Any math will tell you that.

00:09:53,993 --> 00:09:56,729
No, and the only reason
they jumped back in

00:09:56,729 --> 00:10:00,967
