your grandma's slippers.

00:21:02,695 --> 00:21:04,230
They're playful, fun,

00:21:04,230 --> 00:21:07,299
and so comfortable, they're
like walking on pillows.

00:21:07,299 --> 00:21:09,802
They come in almost every color
imaginable,

00:21:09,802 --> 00:21:12,238
including our top-selling
leopard and zebra print,

00:21:12,238 --> 00:21:16,408
as well as the red, black, and
white collegiate-licensed design

00:21:16,408 --> 00:21:17,910
of my beloved
Louisville cardinals.

00:21:17,910 --> 00:21:19,078
Ha!

00:21:19,078 --> 00:21:21,113
[ laughter ]

00:21:21,113 --> 00:21:22,982
Also, don't forget about
our cool animal styles --

00:21:22,982 --> 00:21:27,386
lion, tiger, giraffe, and
the ever-tough shark slippers.

00:21:27,386 --> 00:21:30,256
Happy feet are great
for people of all ages.

00:21:30,256 --> 00:21:33,626
Now, sales are great,
but we need your help

00:21:33,626 --> 00:21:35,494
to expand
in our international markets

00:21:35,494 --> 00:21:36,829
as well as to take it
into retail.

00:21:36,829 --> 00:21:37,930
Now, which of you sharks

00:21:37,930 --> 00:21:39,832
is ready to take the walk
with Happy Feet?

00:21:39,832 --> 00:21:41,700
And I know you won't want
to take them off.

00:21:41,700 --> 00:21:43,502
Awesome. Yeah.
Bring them on.
GREINER: Good.

00:21:43,502 --> 00:21:45,204
All right, so, we're gonna do it
a little different.

00:21:45,204 --> 00:21:46,372
I know
where that pair is going.
Mark, you're an athlete,
a basketball guy.

00:21:46,372 --> 00:21:47,439
Yeah, I know.
Basketball guy,
basketball guy.

00:21:47,439 --> 00:21:48,574
Go, hoosiers, baby.
There you go. All right.

00:21:48,574 --> 00:21:49,241
Go, hoosiers.
GREINER: [ laughs ]

00:21:49,241 --> 00:21:50,376
oh, come on, Mark.

00:21:50,376 --> 00:21:51,644
Go, hoosiers.
The hoosiers?

00:21:51,644 --> 00:21:54,246
Barbara, you got the leopard.
Grr. There you go.

00:21:54,246 --> 00:21:56,015
Got to catch it. Oh, see?
HERJAVEC: She's an animal.

00:21:56,015 --> 00:21:58,517
Doggone!
Give me another shot.
I -- but I threw it short,
though.

00:21:58,517 --> 00:22:00,052
[ sighs ] Too bad.

00:22:00,052 --> 00:22:01,821
For the shark
of all sharks, Mr. O'Leary.
O'LEARY: Hey! Love it.

00:22:01,821 --> 00:22:03,823
See, he can't catch,
either!

00:22:03,823 --> 00:22:06,091
All right, Lori.
You're gonna get the neon zebra.

00:22:06,091 --> 00:22:07,893
For you, Robert -- penguin.

00:22:07,893 --> 00:22:08,994
A penguin?!
What the hell is that?!

00:22:08,994 --> 00:22:10,229
I don't know! We came up
with an animal!

00:22:10,229 --> 00:22:12,298
It's just a cute animal!
What am I?!

00:22:12,298 --> 00:22:14,166
What am I,
the friggin' fluffy shark?!
I think about Canada,
I think of penguin.

00:22:14,166 --> 00:22:15,534
What's wrong with that?
Give me the lion.

00:22:15,534 --> 00:22:16,802
I don't want the penguin!

00:22:16,802 --> 00:22:18,804
You want the lion? Okay.
Hold on. Go ahead. Give it back.

00:22:18,804 --> 00:22:20,973
All right.
We'll get you the lion.
I think you'd look good
in a penguin, Robert.

00:22:20,973 --> 00:22:22,374
There we go.
Oh, my gosh.
These are my new shoes!

00:22:22,374 --> 00:22:23,776
All right!
YATES: There we go.

00:22:23,776 --> 00:22:25,544
These are amazing.
They're like moon boots.

00:22:25,544 --> 00:22:27,546
Absolutely.
They're like moon boots.
Exactly.

00:22:27,546 --> 00:22:29,081
CUBAN: I used to have
a pair of moon boots.

00:22:29,081 --> 00:22:30,216
Wow.
HERJAVEC:
They're so comfortable!

00:22:30,216 --> 00:22:32,351
Wow.
They really are.

00:22:32,351 --> 00:22:33,686
See? Look at that.
Wow.

00:22:33,686 --> 00:22:35,221
Look how good he looks
in those sharks.

00:22:35,221 --> 00:22:37,656
HERJAVEC: Wow. Why are these
so comfortable, pat?

00:22:37,656 --> 00:22:39,592
Well, it is -- it's that 1-inch
foam rubber bottom.

00:22:39,592 --> 00:22:41,327
It's a dense foam rubber
that we put in them.

00:22:41,327 --> 00:22:43,095
Just, the whole thing,
when you step down on it,

00:22:43,095 --> 00:22:45,231
it's like walking
on pillows.

00:22:45,231 --> 00:22:47,733
So, pat, $375,000 for 15%.

00:22:47,733 --> 00:22:50,936
Your sales must be amazing!

00:22:50,936 --> 00:22:53,505
We've done $6.5 million
in the last 3 years...

00:22:53,505 --> 00:22:55,441
You got to be kidding.

00:22:55,441 --> 00:22:57,076
...Between internet
and wholesale -- yes.

00:22:57,076 --> 00:22:58,978
HERJAVEC: What are your sales
last year?

00:22:58,978 --> 00:23:00,246
GREINER: What stores --
what stores are you in?
What are your sales
last year?

00:23:00,246 --> 00:23:01,881
Sales last year
were $2.65 million.

00:23:01,881 --> 00:23:04,350
And the year before?
Uh, $2.4 million.

00:23:04,350 --> 00:23:07,453
So, pat,
out of the $2.6 million,
what percentage is online?

00:23:07,453 --> 00:23:08,988
It's -- actually,
of that $2.6 million,

00:23:08,988 --> 00:23:10,389
it was probably
about $2.2 million,

00:23:10,389 --> 00:23:12,358
which is
the highest margin portion.

00:23:12,358 --> 00:23:15,294
You're selling that
much stuff online? Wow.
Wow.

00:23:15,294 --> 00:23:16,495
And what does it
cost you to make?

00:23:16,495 --> 00:23:18,330
The sneaker-slipper styles
cost about $5.50.

00:23:18,330 --> 00:23:20,933
We sell them $24.99 to $29.99,

00:23:20,933 --> 00:23:22,635
which is about a 400% markup
right there.

00:23:22,635 --> 00:23:24,436
That's a great margin.

00:23:24,436 --> 00:23:25,804
Pat, that $2.6 million
you sold last year --

00:23:25,804 --> 00:23:26,906
what was your profit
on that?

00:23:26,906 --> 00:23:28,274
About $600,000.

00:23:28,274 --> 00:23:29,808
So, where are you spending
all your money?

00:23:29,808 --> 00:23:33,045
Um...
Because with that big
of margins,

00:23:33,045 --> 00:23:34,980
you should be making
more than $600,000.

00:23:34,980 --> 00:23:36,982
We do a ton of free shipping
at our busiest time,

00:23:36,982 --> 00:23:39,485
which is holiday, which knocks
that margin down significantly.

00:23:39,485 --> 00:23:40,719
But the problem was, the margin

00:23:40,719 --> 00:23:42,254
and the seasonality
of the business

00:23:42,254 --> 00:23:44,790
being a little bit seasonal
in the winter,

00:23:44,790 --> 00:23:46,859
it's sort of shot down
some of those profits,
and I didn't have --

00:23:46,859 --> 00:23:48,627
why haven't you focused
on getting

00:23:48,627 --> 00:23:50,796
into major retail stores?

00:23:50,796 --> 00:23:52,364
Well, there are
several reasons.

00:23:52,364 --> 00:23:53,666
Okay.
Number one --
the size of the product.

00:23:53,666 --> 00:23:55,034
They were afraid
it was too big.
Exactly.

00:23:55,034 --> 00:23:57,436
O'LEARY: It takes up 2 1/2 times
the linear square feet

00:23:57,436 --> 00:23:59,438
that an ordinary shoe
would take.

00:23:59,438 --> 00:24:01,407
It is.
It's never gonna go
into retail.

00:24:01,407 --> 00:24:03,409
O'LEARY: I have
a different problem with it.

00:24:03,409 --> 00:24:04,710
You got to help me with this,

00:24:04,710 --> 00:24:06,912
'cause this is the thing
that's bugging me the most.

00:24:06,912 --> 00:24:09,615
There's nothing proprietary
about this stuff.

00:24:09,615 --> 00:24:12,117
I'm very worried
that someone else

00:24:12,117 --> 00:24:15,487
is gonna come in here
and drop the prices by 30%.

00:24:15,487 --> 00:24:16,922
Yeah.

00:24:16,922 --> 00:24:18,757
...Because I've never seen
margins like this in slippers.

00:24:18,757 --> 00:24:20,526
Like, this is incredible.

00:24:20,526 --> 00:24:22,695
Do you have competitors
that are doing the same thing?

00:24:22,695 --> 00:24:24,463
We -- we don't.
Anybody that you see

00:24:24,463 --> 00:24:26,832
selling these online
are buying from us.

00:24:26,832 --> 00:24:30,035
GREINER: How are people
knowing you're there?

00:24:30,035 --> 00:24:31,837
This is the thing
I want to understand,

00:24:31,837 --> 00:24:33,806
'cause you have
an amazing online business.

00:24:33,806 --> 00:24:36,542
We also did a license with a
girl who was on a reality show

00:24:36,542 --> 00:24:39,011
that really built a lot
of social following behind it

00:24:39,011 --> 00:24:40,913
that we still have, as well.
who?
Snooki.

00:24:40,913 --> 00:24:42,348
We utilized her Twitter account
as well as her social,

00:24:42,348 --> 00:24:43,882
to be able to grow it.
who is it?
was it Snooki?

00:24:43,882 --> 00:24:46,051
Another -- yeah.
[ chuckles ]

00:24:46,051 --> 00:24:47,720
and we ended up getting
onto a business

00:24:47,720 --> 00:24:49,555
where we could find
those mid-level social stars

00:24:49,555 --> 00:24:51,490
that would help get our name
out there and grow it.

00:24:51,490 --> 00:24:53,058
Are you saying
Snooki's mid-level?

00:24:53,058 --> 00:24:54,526
She was
when we found her.

00:24:54,526 --> 00:24:56,095
[ laughter ]
She won't like
that I said that.

00:24:56,095 --> 00:24:58,263
But she's fantastic.
Wow. Wow.

00:24:58,263 --> 00:25:01,200
And how much are you having
to pay for those folks?
Uh, it's about 12%.

00:25:01,200 --> 00:25:03,969
Ah, therein lies --
that's where
the money's going.

00:25:03,969 --> 00:25:05,070
That's where the money --
it's not --
it's not all of it

00:25:05,070 --> 00:25:06,238
going to that,
though, Mark.
no, but --

00:25:06,238 --> 00:25:07,906
but it's actually fed
what we're growing.

00:25:07,906 --> 00:25:09,842
So we've really tried to create
our own marketing.

00:25:09,842 --> 00:25:11,510
That's really what I'm about.

00:25:11,510 --> 00:25:12,578
So, proprietary's important,

00:25:12,578 --> 00:25:13,946
but when you have
someone like me

00:25:13,946 --> 00:25:15,948
that's gonna go out and try
to market and work hard --

00:25:15,948 --> 00:25:17,383
pat, you're killing it!

00:25:17,383 --> 00:25:18,450
Well -- right!

00:25:18,450 --> 00:25:19,918
CORCORAN:
Pat, time out for a moment.

00:25:19,918 --> 00:25:22,955
There's something that's
really disturbing me.

00:25:22,955 --> 00:25:26,058
You know, it feels to me
as though you may have peaked

00:25:26,058 --> 00:25:28,594
or are maybe
even on the way down.

00:25:28,594 --> 00:25:31,864
But it feels to me you're not
going to get bigger. I'm out.

00:25:34,033 --> 00:25:37,669
I mean --
pat, look, you --
great business, right?

00:25:37,669 --> 00:25:39,505
I'm an intense entrepreneur,
Robert.

00:25:39,505 --> 00:25:41,473
Oh, my friend,
I get that from you.

00:25:41,473 --> 00:25:42,708
This is
a real business.

00:25:42,708 --> 00:25:44,076
Right.

00:25:44,076 --> 00:25:46,512
You've done
a fantastic job.

00:25:46,512 --> 00:25:49,548
Pat, I-I don't see
where I add value.
I like to add value.

00:25:49,548 --> 00:25:51,617
I'm a good operator,
just like you are.

00:25:51,617 --> 00:25:54,653
I like to run things.
I like to add value to people.

00:25:54,653 --> 00:25:55,988
I don't like to just write
a check to something.

00:25:55,988 --> 00:25:57,022
Let me ask you
one other question,

00:25:57,022 --> 00:25:58,424
one thing
I was gonna talk about.

00:25:58,424 --> 00:26:01,160
Look, I-I don't want you
to waste all your time with me.

00:26:01,160 --> 00:26:02,461
You're doing a great job.

00:26:02,461 --> 00:26:05,097
I don't want to write a check,
and that's it. I'm out.

00:26:05,097 --> 00:26:07,933
Thank you, Robert.
I understand.

00:26:07,933 --> 00:26:09,802
O'LEARY: How many pair
are you gonna sell this year?

00:26:09,802 --> 00:26:12,104
75,000 to 100,000.

00:26:12,104 --> 00:26:15,274
The challenge is,
15% is nothing, nothing to me.

00:26:15,274 --> 00:26:18,110
Right.
It just --
it's not exciting.

00:26:18,110 --> 00:26:19,378
I understand.

00:26:19,378 --> 00:26:21,180
But I understand partnering
with a shark

00:26:21,180 --> 00:26:23,115
isn't a bad thing
for this online business,

00:26:23,115 --> 00:26:26,318
because together, we could
probably sell a ton more.

00:26:26,318 --> 00:26:28,287
I'm gonna make you
an offer.

00:26:30,556 --> 00:26:32,691
I'll give you $375,000,

00:26:32,691 --> 00:26:37,096
and I want a $3 royalty
on every pair sold

00:26:37,096 --> 00:26:38,931
until I get
my $375,000 back.

00:26:38,931 --> 00:26:40,899
[ laughter ]

00:26:40,899 --> 00:26:42,468
Chimed right in.

00:26:42,468 --> 00:26:44,103
Let's see him
make an offer.

00:26:44,103 --> 00:26:45,337
He likes to make
a lot of noise

00:26:45,337 --> 00:26:46,872
but doesn't often make
an offer.
no, it just --

00:26:46,872 --> 00:26:52,578
I want a 5% -- as I like to say,
"wet my beak" -- equity,

00:26:52,578 --> 00:26:54,580
just so we can say
we're partners.

00:26:54,580 --> 00:26:58,817
And I'll -- after I recoup
my capital, I'll drop down
to $1.50.

00:26:58,817 --> 00:27:00,519
That's three times more
than Snooki got!

00:27:00,519 --> 00:27:03,455
Look. I love Snooki,
but you got Mr. Wonderful here.

00:27:03,455 --> 00:27:04,523
That's a whole
different ballgame.

00:27:04,523 --> 00:27:05,891
GREINER: I like it.

00:27:05,891 --> 00:27:08,994
I might offer to go in with
Kevin, if he would have me...

00:27:08,994 --> 00:27:14,600
If you can convince me,
because I like to go bigger.

00:27:14,600 --> 00:27:18,637
I think it would be great
if you could expand into retail.

00:27:18,637 --> 00:27:20,305
So, Lori, I just want
to confirm something.
Okay.

00:27:20,305 --> 00:27:22,441
You want to go 50/50
on the deal.
Yes.

00:27:22,441 --> 00:27:24,543
One modification
we have to make --

00:27:24,543 --> 00:27:26,812
I believe that decimals
are bad karma,

00:27:26,812 --> 00:27:28,914
so you have to go up to 6%
on the "wet your beak" equity.

00:27:28,914 --> 00:27:29,915
[ laughs ]

00:27:29,915 --> 00:27:32,284
So it's 3% each, okay?

00:27:32,284 --> 00:27:34,153
We give him $375,000.
We split that.

00:27:34,153 --> 00:27:37,523
And your one covenant is
that he attempt retail again.

00:27:37,523 --> 00:27:38,790
Yes.

00:27:38,790 --> 00:27:41,693
I am prepared to go on there
and Snooki it out.

00:27:41,693 --> 00:27:43,328
Snooki it out, huh?

00:27:43,328 --> 00:27:44,863
Well, who needs Snooki
when you got pookie?

00:27:44,863 --> 00:27:46,732
I think Mark should jump
all over this.

00:27:46,732 --> 00:27:49,401
Mark, I-I hope
that you see the passion.

00:27:49,401 --> 00:27:50,903
I mean, I've heard you talk
about entrepreneurs.

00:27:50,903 --> 00:27:52,404
And you sold garbage bags,
right?
Door to door.

00:27:52,404 --> 00:27:54,139
I have -- I have a story,
if you'd give me two minutes.
Sure.

00:27:54,139 --> 00:27:55,674
My mom passed away
a year and a half ago

00:27:55,674 --> 00:27:56,875
really kind of unexpectedly,

00:27:56,875 --> 00:27:58,610
and this was
her favorite story of me.

00:27:58,610 --> 00:28:00,312
I had a guy, a kid --

00:28:00,312 --> 00:28:02,281
when I was playing basketball
in the backyard with a kid,

00:28:02,281 --> 00:28:03,448
his dad was throwing
some calendars out.

00:28:03,448 --> 00:28:05,117
I looked at them.
They were last year's calendars.

00:28:05,117 --> 00:28:07,019
I took those, and I literally
walked my way home

